	(1,1,'2013-04-16 22:38:34','2013-04-16 22:38:34','<h2>What To Do When Disaster Strikes?</h2>\r\n<p>I write this post with experience. Long, frustrating and paintful experience. My first hack was on a small site and nothing that a pot of coffee and 4am couldn\'t fix! The Second was on a larger site and after hours of work I was throwing in the white flag. Thankfully, I found some solutions and through my frustrations I am not able to help you out!</p>\r\n<h3>It\'s Not Personal</h3>\r\n<p>First things first. There is a good chance that your site got hacked with a lot of other sites living on the same web server. In other words, the attacker didn\'t seek out your site specifically. In 99.9% of the cases, the hacker targeted a specific host, server or platform. They sent their ugly web robots out by the masses to find security holes and latch on.</p>\r\n<p>The issue with most hacks is finding the security hole which is often called the \"open door\". You will easily spot the hack on your website. Some redirect your site to another url and others throw a bunch of text and links on certain pages. The difficult part is finding and closing the \"open door\" where the hack occurred.</p>\r\n<h3>The Immediate Fix</h3>\r\n<p>The good news is that you can fix and restore your website with a little help. As I said, my second hack experience was on a larger website and I was left scratching my head for a solution. After searching the web for a few hours I discovered a company called Sucuri. They claimed that they would help protect your website for 1 year and fix any current issues or hacks that you may have. Knowing that my client really wanted their website up and I could see no clear option, I decided to drop the $89 fee and see if they could walk the talk.</p>\r\n<p>It was 11:30pm when I signed up for the Sucuri service. At 1:30am I received an email informing me that my website was restored. I rolled over in my bed, grabbed my phone and pulled up the website. Just as they promised the site was as clean as a whistle. (Which I assume is pretty clean!)</p>\r\n<h3>How to Stay Clean</h3>\r\n<p>There are several preventive maintenance tips that you can use to keep your website hacker free. Nothing is 100% but I am going to follow this post up with some of helpful advice. For now, head to Sucuri.net and go to bed!</p>\r\n','Help, we just got hacked!','','publish','open','open','','hello-world','','','2013-05-06 03:55:13','2013-05-06 03:55:13','',0,'http://localhost:8888/jeremybasham_finalproject_wp/wordpress/?p=1',0,'post','',1),
	(2,1,'2013-04-16 22:38:34','2013-04-16 22:38:34','This is an example page. It\'s different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:\n\n<blockquote>Hi there! I\'m a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my blog. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like pi&#241;a coladas. (And gettin\' caught in the rain.)</blockquote>\n\n...or something like this:\n\n<blockquote>The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickeys to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.</blockquote>\n\nAs a new WordPress user, you should go to <a href=\"http://localhost:8888/jeremybasham_finalproject_wp/wordpress/wp-admin/\">your dashboard</a> to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!','Sample Page','','publish','open','open','','sample-page','','','2013-04-16 22:38:34','2013-04-16 22:38:34','',0,'http://localhost:8888/jeremybasham_finalproject_wp/wordpress/?page_id=2',0,'page','',0),
