	(28,1,'2013-04-22 03:20:26','2013-04-22 03:20:26','It\'s all too familiar. You have a lot to get done so you are hoping for a quick website update. Your big event is tonight and you need to add a little more information to your event page. You type in your url and your site redirects to a page that is definitely not your church\'s website! You try again just to make sure. Yep, you\'ve been hacked!\r\n\r\nOkay, so now what? Well, it’s not the end of the world. It may seem like it but just stay tuned and I’ll help you make sense of it all and get your site back to normal.  Trust me, I have been there. More than once actually! So I understand the overwhelming feeling of defeat and panic. The good news, I’ve been there, conquered it and was able to restore my site without too much effort. You ready?\r\n\r\nThe first time one of my websites got hacked was painful. It was a small WordPress website that I have created for a church plant. The pastor called me up one night in a panic becuase he discovered that the website was being redirected to other sites everytime someone tried to view it on a mobile device. And believe me, it was not sending people to a very wholesome website! I remained calm while I was on the phone. But I admit it. When we hung up, I didn’t have a clue!\r\n\r\nThe good news is that WordPress does some neat things with it’s file structure. In particular, it separates the design files from the content and database. The bad news is that the hack is usually buried deep within one of the many theme files. Knowing something had to be done, I took a stab at a solution. my thought was to back up the whole database of content (the images, blog posts, and page information), delete all the design/theme files, and basically start again. Thankfully, I had the right approach. Unfortunately, it was easy said than done.\r\n\r\nThe second time around was not so pretty. It was a large website used by a whole church conference. This time, the attack left links all in the header of the website. I spent hours trying to resolve the issues but couldn’t figure it out. I think I spent 4 hours or more just reading web design forums desperately looking for the answer. Finally, I discovered a company that could help and hopefully, I signed up for their services around 11:30pm. By 1pm, I received an email that the issue had been resolved!\r\n\r\nThe company is called Sucuri and they provide a service to find, remove and protect your website from hackers...','Help, we just got hacked!','','inherit','open','open','','1-revision-6','','','2013-04-22 03:20:26','2013-04-22 03:20:26','',1,'http://localhost:8888/jeremybasham_finalproject_wp/wordpress/?p=28',0,'revision','',0),
